introduction.p:
has no real-valued solutions. Applying the quadratic formula, we find

x=\dfrac{-(-2) \pm \sqrt{(-2)^2-4(1)(2)}}{2} = \dfrac{2 \pm \sqrt{-4}}{2}

The solutions of the equation are \dfrac{2 + \sqrt{-4}}{2} and \dfrac{2 - \sqrt{-4}}{2}, but they are not real numbers. Because \sqrt{-4} is not a real number, the equation x^2-2x+2-0 has no real solutions.

subsection.p:
The letter i used in this way is not a variable, it is the name of a specific number, and hence is a constant. The square root of any negative number can be written as the product of a real number and i.  For example, 
\begin{align*}
  \sqrt{-4} \amp = \sqrt{-1 \cdot 4}\\
    \amp = \sqrt{-1} \sqrt{4} = i \cdot 2\\
    \end{align*}
or \sqrt{-4} = 2i. Any number that is the product of i and a real number is called an imaginary number.

